1
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:12,000
[sleigh bells jingling]

2
00:00:25,291 --> 00:00:26,368
[Jesper] <i>Letters.</i>

3
00:00:26,469 --> 00:00:28,788
<i>You don't really write many these days,
do you?</i>

4
00:00:29,291 --> 00:00:31,460
<i>But I bet there's one you never forget.</i>

5
00:00:31,957 --> 00:00:34,448
<i>Send it off to a certain plump guy
in a red suit</i>

6
00:00:34,548 --> 00:00:36,659
<i>and, provided
you've kept your act together</i>

7
00:00:36,759 --> 00:00:37,759
<i>more or less,</i>

8
00:00:38,082 --> 00:00:39,463
<i>he'll drop off a toy or two.</i>

9
00:00:40,040 --> 00:00:42,033
<i>And yet, no one seems to wonder</i>

10
00:00:42,133 --> 00:00:44,414
<i>how the whole thing
got started in the first place.</i>

11
00:00:45,625 --> 00:00:48,954
<i>This is a story about letters,
and it began...</i>

12
00:00:50,125 --> 00:00:51,125
<i>with this one.</i>

13
00:00:53,457 --> 00:00:55,378
[festive music plays]

14
00:01:15,207 --> 00:01:16,207
[bell ringing]

15
00:01:25,832 --> 00:01:26,923
[whistle blows]

16
00:01:27,707 --> 00:01:29,867
[cadets grunting]

17
00:01:29,968 --> 00:01:32,990
[Drill Sergeant] ...74, 75, 76...

18
00:01:33,090 --> 00:01:36,503
- [grunting continues]
- ...77, 78, 79,

19
00:01:37,082 --> 00:01:38,701
- 80!
- Drill Sergeant, sir!

20
00:01:38,801 --> 00:01:41,670
All the way from the top!
Dispatch for one of your cadets!

21
00:01:43,415 --> 00:01:45,198
It's for him, sir.

22
00:01:45,298 --> 00:01:46,298
[gasps]

23
00:01:46,396 --> 00:01:47,633
[growls]

24
00:01:54,040 --> 00:01:55,409
Cadet Johanssen!

25
00:01:55,509 --> 00:01:57,200
[sips] Mmm-mmm-mmm!

26
00:01:57,299 --> 00:01:58,299
Stop.

27
00:01:58,399 --> 00:02:00,421
Don't tell me. Let me try to guess.

28
00:02:01,250 --> 00:02:02,409
I give up. Who are you?

29
00:02:02,510 --> 00:02:03,510
Sarge!

30
00:02:03,608 --> 00:02:06,004
Drill Sarge! Have a seat.
Can I get you something to drink?

31
00:02:06,105 --> 00:02:07,143
An espresso? A cappuccino?

32
00:02:07,242 --> 00:02:10,449
Aren't you supposed to be
in equestrian training?

33
00:02:10,549 --> 00:02:11,549
Mmm-hmm. Mmm-hmm.

34
00:02:11,647 --> 00:02:13,750
No worries.
I've got someone covering for me.

35
00:02:17,832 --> 00:02:21,742
[groans] Dispatch
from the Postmaster General's Office!

36
00:02:21,842 --> 00:02:22,842
What?

37
00:02:22,942 --> 00:02:24,073
Sarge, is that for real?

38
00:02:24,173 --> 00:02:25,989
Don't tease me now. [chuckles]

39
00:02:26,088 --> 00:02:27,133
Here, hold these.

40
00:02:28,750 --> 00:02:30,909
Ah, well, I was expecting this
a little bit sooner,

41
00:02:31,009 --> 00:02:34,531
but, yup, summoned to the dragon's lair.

42
00:02:34,632 --> 00:02:37,865
Go ahead and cancel
the Drill Sergeant's espresso, actually.

43
00:02:37,966 --> 00:02:39,643
And, uh, here, why don't you finish
mine?

44
00:02:39,742 --> 00:02:41,819
- I'm not gonna be needing it anymore...
- [growls]

45
00:02:41,920 --> 00:02:44,995
...and I'm gonna take one last look
around the old place so I can forget it.

46
00:02:45,094 --> 00:02:46,990
Mmm-hmm. Got it. All right, let's go.

47
00:02:47,091 --> 00:02:48,091
[growls]

48
00:02:50,250 --> 00:02:51,829
[Postmaster] Nine months.

49
00:02:52,665 --> 00:02:57,239
It's been nine months
since I used every ounce of my influence

50
00:02:57,338 --> 00:02:59,324
to get you into the Royal Postal
Academy.

51
00:02:59,424 --> 00:03:02,698
Actually, nine months and six days,
but who's counting?

52
00:03:02,798 --> 00:03:04,323
What? No croutons?

53
00:03:04,423 --> 00:03:06,157
Oh, man, come on!

54
00:03:06,258 --> 00:03:08,490
Shall we take account
of your progress then?

55
00:03:08,591 --> 00:03:10,161
Mmm-hmm. Mmm-hmm. Mmm-hmm. Definitely.

56
00:03:10,260 --> 00:03:11,897
- Sergeant.
- [Drill Sergeant] Yes, sir!

57
00:03:11,997 --> 00:03:13,036
Sorting and filing:

58
00:03:14,790 --> 00:03:16,659
<i>total failure.</i>

59
00:03:16,759 --> 00:03:18,618
<i>Carrier pigeon care and handling...</i>

60
00:03:18,718 --> 00:03:19,718
[pigeon coos]

61
00:03:20,165 --> 00:03:22,070
<i>...abysmal performance.</i>

62
00:03:22,170 --> 00:03:24,616
<i>- Transport of fragile merchandise...</i>
- [Jesper whistling]

63
00:03:24,716 --> 00:03:26,578
<i>...worst on record.</i>

64
00:03:27,165 --> 00:03:28,165
Well, there you have it.

65
00:03:28,264 --> 00:03:30,828
But, hey, we gave it the old college
try,
didn't we?

66
00:03:31,375 --> 00:03:34,030
Guess I'll just go pack up
and head home then. Too bad.

67
00:03:34,129 --> 00:03:35,319
Darn, oh, darn.

68
00:03:35,420 --> 00:03:37,325
- Stay right where you are.
- No, Dad!

69
00:03:37,457 --> 00:03:39,740
You're right. When will I grow up?

70
00:03:39,840 --> 00:03:43,033
When will I stop squandering
all these opportunities,

71
00:03:43,134 --> 00:03:45,239
which you so kindly forced me into,

72
00:03:45,338 --> 00:03:46,620
and become my own man?

73
00:03:46,719 --> 00:03:50,490
I guess I must really hanker down
and rethink my priorities.

74
00:03:50,590 --> 00:03:53,783
All wrapped up in my silk sheets
with some caviar and a sherry...

75
00:03:53,884 --> 00:03:55,322
You still buy the same brand, right?

76
00:03:55,421 --> 00:03:57,658
You think I'm just going to
watch you purposely fail

77
00:03:57,758 --> 00:03:59,699
and then let you waltz right back

78
00:03:59,800 --> 00:04:02,573
to a privileged life
void of any purpose or meaning?

79
00:04:02,673 --> 00:04:05,407
Well, yeah. Where else would I...

80
00:04:05,508 --> 00:04:09,282
Congratulations. You are now a postman.

81
00:04:09,382 --> 00:04:10,907
- [gasps]
- Come again?

82
00:04:11,007 --> 00:04:15,129
You are to establish
a working postal office in...

83
00:04:25,332 --> 00:04:27,082
Smeerensburg.

84
00:04:27,875 --> 00:04:28,906
You've got one year.

85
00:04:29,007 --> 00:04:31,160
What? A year? Where? Smeerensburg?

86
00:04:31,259 --> 00:04:33,018
What is...
What's happening right now? Dad?

87
00:04:33,117 --> 00:04:34,781
Six thousand letters will suffice.

88
00:04:34,880 --> 00:04:36,406
Stamped by your own hand.

89
00:04:36,507 --> 00:04:38,119
And listen carefully, Jesper.

90
00:04:38,218 --> 00:04:41,418
If you fail to get those letters,
you're cut off.

91
00:04:41,957 --> 00:04:43,658
No more fancy apartments,

92
00:04:43,759 --> 00:04:45,699
- stagecoach, clothes, galas...
- [grunts]

93
00:04:45,800 --> 00:04:46,992
All gone.

94
00:04:47,091 --> 00:04:49,870
You can look forward to
a cozy spot in the gutter.

95
00:04:49,970 --> 00:04:52,572
- But...
- Six thousand letters, one year.

96
00:04:52,672 --> 00:04:55,625
You can't cheat, bribe
or squirm your way out of this one.

97
00:04:57,125 --> 00:05:01,319
Dad! Come on!
It's me. Let's talk about this, man.

98
00:05:01,420 --> 00:05:04,447
It's your son, Jesper! Little Jespie!

99
00:05:04,548 --> 00:05:07,572
Remember, I...
"Daddy, can I help you mail the letters?

100
00:05:07,673 --> 00:05:10,197
Can I help you put the medals
in the letters

101
00:05:10,298 --> 00:05:12,072
and put them in a stamp with the..."

102
00:05:12,173 --> 00:05:13,571
W-w-wait!

103
00:05:13,670 --> 00:05:15,915
Do you know how long it took
to press this uniform?

104
00:05:16,500 --> 00:05:18,949
I don't either,
but it took somebody hours.

105
00:05:19,050 --> 00:05:20,050
Hello?

106
00:05:20,540 --> 00:05:23,500
Burghard! Finally, a friendly face.
Can you believe what they...

107
00:05:24,082 --> 00:05:27,043
Burghard, I'm not in the coach with you.
Burghard?

108
00:05:31,790 --> 00:05:36,033
[Drill Sergeant] Sir,
I'm all for
discipline, but Smeerensburg?

109
00:05:36,132 --> 00:05:38,697
Isn't that a bit excessive?

110
00:05:38,798 --> 00:05:40,033
[sighs]

111
00:05:40,132 --> 00:05:43,415
That boy needs a wake-up call, Sergeant.
And who knows?

112
00:05:43,957 --> 00:05:47,127
Someday he might even thank me for it.

113
00:05:47,790 --> 00:05:49,242
[sarcastically] Thank you, Dad!

114
00:05:49,341 --> 00:05:52,574
This is really wonderful, Father.
Thank you so much.

115
00:05:52,673 --> 00:05:54,367
This is great, Dad.

116
00:05:54,466 --> 00:05:56,077
Really, really great.

117
00:06:00,125 --> 00:06:01,238
Thanks, Dad!

118
00:06:01,338 --> 00:06:02,742
[strains and grunts]

119
00:06:02,843 --> 00:06:03,843
Thank you!

120
00:06:03,942 --> 00:06:06,201
I love this terrible coach ride.

121
00:06:06,300 --> 00:06:07,533
Thank you so much!

122
00:06:07,632 --> 00:06:10,245
Thank you. Thank you. Thank you.
Thank...

123
00:06:24,707 --> 00:06:25,707
[huffs]

124
00:06:26,165 --> 00:06:28,029
[clears throat]

125
00:06:28,129 --> 00:06:31,779
You go back to the intersection.
You make a left at the dead tree.

126
00:06:31,879 --> 00:06:32,879
You're welcome.

127
00:06:33,415 --> 00:06:35,071
What? No. I'm not lost.

128
00:06:35,170 --> 00:06:36,617
Trust me, you are.

129
00:06:36,716 --> 00:06:39,367
[laughs] Funny! Say, nice boat!

130
00:06:39,468 --> 00:06:41,627
Any chance you might
actually get on it today?

131
00:06:43,165 --> 00:06:44,821
What was that?

132
00:06:44,920 --> 00:06:47,321
New postman. Smeerensburg.

133
00:06:47,420 --> 00:06:49,738
Which is on an island,
which is surrounded by water,

134
00:06:49,838 --> 00:06:52,074
which I need a boat to get to,
which you have.

135
00:06:52,173 --> 00:06:54,456
Are we starting to connect the dots?

136
00:06:55,332 --> 00:06:56,463
[chuckles]

137
00:07:00,040 --> 00:07:02,040
[Mogens whistling]

138
00:07:04,040 --> 00:07:05,910
Is the weather always like this?

139
00:07:06,009 --> 00:07:08,290
Eh. We're having a bit of a heat wave.

140
00:07:12,125 --> 00:07:13,125
Huh?

141
00:07:27,250 --> 00:07:30,459
There she is. Smeerensburg.

142
00:07:34,000 --> 00:07:36,990
Charming, huh?
Why, you should see it in the spring.

143
00:07:37,091 --> 00:07:40,173
That's when those grays really pop.

144
00:07:42,332 --> 00:07:44,332
[Mogens whistling]

145
00:07:48,665 --> 00:07:50,408
What happened here?

146
00:07:50,507 --> 00:07:54,949
Oh! Uh, colorful local traditions.
Quirky folklore. That kind of thing.

147
00:07:55,050 --> 00:07:58,500
All part of this quaint town's
vibrant culture.

148
00:08:00,250 --> 00:08:01,250
[children giggling]

149
00:08:01,348 --> 00:08:03,283
No, no! Why you...

150
00:08:03,382 --> 00:08:07,035
Oh, you rotten vermin! [yelling]

151
00:08:13,375 --> 00:08:14,824
[shushes]

152
00:08:37,290 --> 00:08:38,451
Where is everyone?

153
00:08:38,551 --> 00:08:39,551
Everyone?

154
00:08:39,649 --> 00:08:42,375
I thought there would be
some sort of a reception.

155
00:08:43,832 --> 00:08:47,743
Oh! Right. Right, the reception.
Of course, the reception.

156
00:08:47,842 --> 00:08:48,880
It's good you reminded me.

157
00:08:48,980 --> 00:08:53,029
You just ring the bell over there and,
uh... and then the reception will start.

158
00:08:53,129 --> 00:08:55,447
- The bell?
- Yep. Give it a go.

159
00:08:55,548 --> 00:08:56,572
And they'll come out.

160
00:08:56,673 --> 00:09:01,197
Why, they'll have a band, hors d'oeuvres
and, uh... and the key to the city.

161
00:09:01,298 --> 00:09:03,072
All that reception stuff.

162
00:09:03,173 --> 00:09:04,239
Really?

163
00:09:04,339 --> 00:09:06,743
- Out here?
- Why, of course!

164
00:09:06,842 --> 00:09:11,462
Well, it's not every day they get
a brand-new postman from the big city.

165
00:09:14,250 --> 00:09:16,250
[bell ringing]

166
00:09:17,916 --> 00:09:19,658
[all yelling and clamoring]

167
00:09:19,758 --> 00:09:20,758
Huh?

168
00:09:21,009 --> 00:09:23,039
[clamoring continues]

169
00:09:30,166 --> 00:09:33,326
What's happening?

170
00:09:37,207 --> 00:09:38,822
[gasping]

171
00:09:38,922 --> 00:09:39,922
[screams]

172
00:09:40,020 --> 00:09:41,366
[panting]

173
00:09:41,466 --> 00:09:43,118
- Whoa! Whoa! [gasps]
- [man groans]

174
00:09:43,217 --> 00:09:45,327
- [roars]
- [Jesper] Aah!

175
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:48,580
Ow, they're biting!
Ow, get off! Get off! Get off!

176
00:09:50,250 --> 00:09:51,490
[shudders]

177
00:09:51,591 --> 00:09:52,712
[yelps]

178
00:09:53,290 --> 00:09:54,741
[Mogens] Isn't this nice?

179
00:09:54,841 --> 00:09:56,411
And you thought they forgot.

180
00:09:56,510 --> 00:09:58,000
Quick! Get me out of here! [screams]

181
00:09:59,500 --> 00:10:01,500
[continues screaming]

182
00:10:15,207 --> 00:10:17,322
- Uh...
- What's going on out here?

183
00:10:17,422 --> 00:10:19,857
- Why is everybody just standing around?
- [Mrs. Krum] Well!

184
00:10:19,957 --> 00:10:22,490
Look who's finally throwing in the
towel!

185
00:10:22,590 --> 00:10:24,201
Throwing in the... Us?

186
00:10:24,302 --> 00:10:25,533
Ha! That's rich!

187
00:10:25,633 --> 00:10:29,279
Admit it!
You weaseled out and rang the bell!

188
00:10:29,379 --> 00:10:32,197
[Mr. Ellingboe] An Ellingboe? Never!
It was one of you critters!

189
00:10:32,298 --> 00:10:33,816
Don't you dare raise your voice at me!

190
00:10:33,915 --> 00:10:35,594
- Oh, there you go!
- You rang that bell!

191
00:10:35,693 --> 00:10:37,611
- You know you rang... Oh!
- [Magdalone growls]

192
00:10:37,711 --> 00:10:40,389
[Mr. Ellingboe] You chicken out,
and now you want to pin it on us!

193
00:10:40,489 --> 00:10:42,804
- [Mrs. Krum] Unbelievable!
- We were plowing the snow...

194
00:10:42,904 --> 00:10:43,904
[Jesper] Oh, whoa! Hey!

195
00:10:44,004 --> 00:10:45,481
Huh. What've you got there, children?

196
00:10:45,581 --> 00:10:46,740
- Mine!
- [Jesper straining]

197
00:10:46,840 --> 00:10:48,869
Pumpkin, show Daddy what you found.

198
00:10:48,969 --> 00:10:50,368
[continues straining]

199
00:10:50,467 --> 00:10:51,467
[huffs]

200
00:10:52,540 --> 00:10:53,540
Mine.

201
00:10:53,639 --> 00:10:55,081
[gasping]

202
00:10:56,000 --> 00:10:57,990
This is no way to treat a person!

203
00:10:58,091 --> 00:11:00,283
Certainly not this person!

204
00:11:00,384 --> 00:11:01,739
Just one second. Let me just...

205
00:11:01,839 --> 00:11:02,839
A postman?

206
00:11:02,937 --> 00:11:05,073
- Pfft. Give me a break.
- When will they learn?

207
00:11:05,173 --> 00:11:07,947
Hey! They've sent us another postman!

208
00:11:08,048 --> 00:11:09,831
[all laughing]

209
00:11:11,666 --> 00:11:13,279
All right. All right.

210
00:11:13,379 --> 00:11:16,029
You don't know who I am,
so I'm gonna let this one slide.

211
00:11:16,129 --> 00:11:18,989
Okay? But let's just say
I'm not really a postman.

212
00:11:19,088 --> 00:11:22,243
Well, I am, because it's
our family business. My father's a...

213
00:11:22,342 --> 00:11:25,577
- Don't get me started, because it's...
- Where were we? Oh, yeah. Bell, please!

214
00:11:25,677 --> 00:11:27,355
- [chuckles]
- [Jesper] Life is too short

215
00:11:27,456 --> 00:11:29,892
- to go into details, but... [gasps]
- [villagers clamoring]

216
00:11:29,991 --> 00:11:31,169
[exclaiming]

217
00:11:36,082 --> 00:11:38,423
[grunts and pants]

218
00:11:39,290 --> 00:11:40,822
[panting]

219
00:11:40,923 --> 00:11:43,071
[Alva] Come to the counter.
I'll be right out.

220
00:11:43,171 --> 00:11:44,171
All right, listen.

221
00:11:44,269 --> 00:11:48,780
Whoever's there, I warn you,
you do not want to mess with me. Okay?

222
00:11:48,880 --> 00:11:51,365
Holy mackerel! Oh, the smell!

223
00:11:51,466 --> 00:11:54,118
Fresh out of mackerel.
Only herring and burbot today.

224
00:11:54,217 --> 00:11:55,217
[grunts]

225
00:11:59,332 --> 00:12:00,332
Oh. [retches]

226
00:12:00,750 --> 00:12:01,750
Oh.

227
00:12:01,849 --> 00:12:05,659
Uniform, cold sweat, scared stiff,
shaking in your boots.

228
00:12:05,759 --> 00:12:08,409
All right, I'm gonna just
take a wild guess here.

229
00:12:08,509 --> 00:12:11,119
You are the latest mailman,

230
00:12:11,219 --> 00:12:14,408
and the ferryman tricked you
into ringing the Battle Bell.

231
00:12:14,509 --> 00:12:17,822
The Battle Bell?
What kind of a town has a Battle Bell?

232
00:12:17,923 --> 00:12:20,599
Can we open a window in here or
something?
I can't pretend any...

233
00:12:20,698 --> 00:12:22,735
- [villagers clamoring]
- Welcome to Smeerensburg,

234
00:12:22,836 --> 00:12:24,918
home of the world's finest feuds.

235
00:12:25,500 --> 00:12:26,500
Feuds?

236
00:12:26,599 --> 00:12:28,235
- [object falling]
- Grudges, bickering,

237
00:12:28,336 --> 00:12:30,666
the Krums versus the Ellingboes.

238
00:12:31,166 --> 00:12:32,484
- So...
- [object lands heavily]

239
00:12:32,584 --> 00:12:35,495
...are you gonna buy something,
or are you just here to chitchat?

240
00:12:36,040 --> 00:12:37,040
Wait.

241
00:12:37,540 --> 00:12:41,241
Isn't this a school?
Shouldn't there be
children and a teacher?

242
00:12:41,341 --> 00:12:44,161
Oh! Yes! Oh, thank you! Thank you!

243
00:12:44,260 --> 00:12:46,490
I knew I was forgetting something!
Children!

244
00:12:46,591 --> 00:12:47,673
Thank you!

245
00:12:48,415 --> 00:12:49,415
You're the teacher?

246
00:12:49,514 --> 00:12:50,739
Okay, here's how it works.

247
00:12:50,838 --> 00:12:53,594
I sell fish, and then the person
on the other side of the counter...

248
00:12:53,693 --> 00:12:56,830
- That would be you. You buy...
- Holy moly! That's you?

249
00:12:57,500 --> 00:12:58,950
What happened?

250
00:12:59,049 --> 00:13:01,285
- What happened was...
- That's... That came out wrong.

251
00:13:01,385 --> 00:13:02,385
I took a teaching job

252
00:13:02,485 --> 00:13:05,365
at a place where people
don't send their kids to school!

253
00:13:05,466 --> 00:13:07,782
- [splutters]
- Mingling with their
sworn enemy's spawn?

254
00:13:07,881 --> 00:13:09,599
- [exclaims]
- Oh, no! We can't have that!

255
00:13:09,698 --> 00:13:13,119
So, now I'm reduced to doing this
so I can get some money

256
00:13:13,219 --> 00:13:17,378
and start fresh
somewhere far, far away from here.

257
00:13:17,916 --> 00:13:20,666
Are you going to buy something?

258
00:13:21,457 --> 00:13:22,827
Herring's on sale today.

259
00:13:23,625 --> 00:13:24,657
[door opens]

260
00:13:24,756 --> 00:13:27,740
Ah! There you are.
I wondered where you'd scurried off to!

261
00:13:27,841 --> 00:13:29,243
Morning, Miss. Alva.

262
00:13:29,342 --> 00:13:31,573
- [Alva] Mogens.
- Come on, sport!

263
00:13:31,673 --> 00:13:33,786
I saved the best for last!

264
00:13:39,582 --> 00:13:41,003
Home sweet home.

265
00:13:42,332 --> 00:13:44,201
- Ow! What the...
- [boy laughs]

266
00:13:44,302 --> 00:13:47,369
- Mail that, postman!
- Now wait a
minute, that's completely...

267
00:13:47,469 --> 00:13:48,990
Go home, you loser!

268
00:13:49,090 --> 00:13:52,911
Oh, yeah? Well, if I'm a loser,
then you're a, uh...

269
00:13:53,010 --> 00:13:54,789
You're too far. You're gone.

270
00:13:55,915 --> 00:13:56,915
[Mogens grunts]

271
00:13:57,014 --> 00:13:58,875
[clucking]

272
00:14:02,666 --> 00:14:04,821
Well, lots of nice, natural light,

273
00:14:04,921 --> 00:14:07,779
rustic touches, central air
and panoramic views.

274
00:14:07,879 --> 00:14:10,075
- Perfect for animal lovers.
- [clucks]

275
00:14:10,832 --> 00:14:12,910
- Enjoy.
- Wait! Wait!

276
00:14:13,010 --> 00:14:14,710
This can't be right! I...

277
00:14:15,416 --> 00:14:19,321
[chuckles] Oh, I get it. Did my father
put you up to this? Good one.

278
00:14:19,421 --> 00:14:20,908
Ha ha. You got me.

279
00:14:21,008 --> 00:14:24,072
Okay, well, enough of that.
Show me where I'm really staying.

280
00:14:24,173 --> 00:14:26,375
I'd like a hot bath
and a look at the dinner menu.

281
00:14:27,250 --> 00:14:29,240
Here, let me help you out. [clears
throat]

282
00:14:29,341 --> 00:14:31,743
You're a postman in Smeerensburg,

283
00:14:31,842 --> 00:14:34,743
which is on an island
cut off from the world,

284
00:14:34,842 --> 00:14:37,201
frigid cold, angry, violent neighbors,

285
00:14:37,302 --> 00:14:39,741
and this is home now.

286
00:14:39,841 --> 00:14:42,293
Are we starting to connect the dots?

287
00:14:45,125 --> 00:14:46,125
Aah!

288
00:14:46,707 --> 00:14:47,707
Ugh.

289
00:15:04,125 --> 00:15:06,495
Almost. Hang in there.

290
00:15:11,832 --> 00:15:13,673
[shivering]

291
00:15:17,832 --> 00:15:19,533
[muttering]

292
00:15:19,634 --> 00:15:20,634
What?

293
00:15:21,791 --> 00:15:23,241
- [crows]
- [grunts]

294
00:15:23,341 --> 00:15:24,633
[screams]

295
00:15:36,207 --> 00:15:37,740
[shuddering]

296
00:15:37,840 --> 00:15:38,840
[screams]

297
00:15:41,790 --> 00:15:42,790
Hmm?

298
00:15:42,889 --> 00:15:43,889
Oh.

299
00:15:44,125 --> 00:15:45,125
[grunts]

300
00:15:46,000 --> 00:15:47,210
- [screeches]
- Aah!

301
00:15:48,457 --> 00:15:51,030
[sobbing] That's it!
This place is the worst!

302
00:15:51,130 --> 00:15:52,130
I'm going home!

303
00:15:52,230 --> 00:15:54,201
No! You can't leave, remember?

304
00:15:54,301 --> 00:15:56,409
You'll be broke! Out in the streets!

305
00:15:56,509 --> 00:15:58,409
But I hate it here!

306
00:15:58,509 --> 00:16:00,119
It's so cold and icky!

307
00:16:00,219 --> 00:16:02,868
And the people are mean to me.
And I miss my silk sheets.

308
00:16:02,967 --> 00:16:05,030
Shut up! Stop being weak!

309
00:16:05,130 --> 00:16:07,197
Focus! How do you get out of here?

310
00:16:07,298 --> 00:16:09,331
You need... You need...

311
00:16:09,916 --> 00:16:11,029
letters!

312
00:16:11,129 --> 00:16:12,129
Ugh.

313
00:16:14,166 --> 00:16:16,408
All right. This is a good one.
I can feel it.

314
00:16:16,508 --> 00:16:18,869
Come to Papa, you sweet, sweet little...

315
00:16:18,969 --> 00:16:20,618
Oh, come on!

316
00:16:20,717 --> 00:16:22,128
Ugh! Pssh!

317
00:16:23,291 --> 00:16:24,291
[retches]

318
00:16:25,000 --> 00:16:26,600
[groans]

319
00:16:30,125 --> 00:16:32,455
Fine. Go to the source, I guess.

320
00:16:33,040 --> 00:16:34,159
Good morning, madame.

321
00:16:34,259 --> 00:16:35,990
I'm the postman, obviously.

322
00:16:36,091 --> 00:16:37,808
If you have letters you'd like me to
send,

323
00:16:37,908 --> 00:16:40,043
you could go scurry ahead
and get them and...

324
00:16:46,250 --> 00:16:47,409
Hello! Hi! Hi!

325
00:16:47,509 --> 00:16:50,306
If you have your letters on you,
I'd be glad to take them off your...

326
00:16:50,405 --> 00:16:51,405
[grunts]

327
00:16:52,165 --> 00:16:53,165
Hmph!

328
00:16:53,264 --> 00:16:55,161
Birthday cards? Distant cousin?

329
00:16:55,260 --> 00:16:56,260
Deceased notice?

330
00:16:56,360 --> 00:16:57,540
Holy mother!

331
00:16:59,040 --> 00:17:02,076
- [screaming] Any letters... or
packages?
- [playing instruments
noisily]

332
00:17:02,176 --> 00:17:03,176
Any packages?

333
00:17:03,274 --> 00:17:04,784
Come on, people!

334
00:17:04,884 --> 00:17:07,779
Letters! Letters! I don't have all day!

335
00:17:07,880 --> 00:17:09,875
- [screams]
- [thugs yell]

336
00:17:10,665 --> 00:17:12,907
Okay, keep low. Don't panic. Don't
panic.

337
00:17:13,008 --> 00:17:15,823
Oh, I guess that's why
they call it "snail mail."

338
00:17:15,923 --> 00:17:16,923
[grunts]

339
00:17:17,021 --> 00:17:19,492
All right. What's going on here?
Where are all the letters?

340
00:17:19,593 --> 00:17:23,173
Oh. Folks around here only have
one thing to say to one another.

341
00:17:24,333 --> 00:17:25,333
Ah.

342
00:17:25,432 --> 00:17:28,031
And they're getting their point across
pretty well without mail.

343
00:17:28,132 --> 00:17:29,739
- Wouldn't you say?
- Wait, wait, wait.

344
00:17:29,838 --> 00:17:33,423
No letters?
But how am I supposed to get out of...

345
00:17:34,415 --> 00:17:36,157
- What the...
- [boy] Hello?

346
00:17:36,258 --> 00:17:38,740
Sir, can I get my drawing back?

347
00:17:38,840 --> 00:17:40,292
The wind blew it away.

348
00:17:40,875 --> 00:17:42,489
- Please?
- Not now, kid.

349
00:17:42,588 --> 00:17:45,583
Can't you see I'm busy
trying to figure out how to get...

350
00:17:46,750 --> 00:17:47,910
Well, here's a thought.

351
00:17:48,009 --> 00:17:49,281
I'm a postman, see?

352
00:17:49,382 --> 00:17:53,448
So I can't give it to you,
but I could mail it to you.

353
00:17:53,548 --> 00:17:55,201
- [boy] How?
- Couldn't be simpler!

354
00:17:55,300 --> 00:17:58,823
I just fold your pretty drawing,
very beautiful by the way,

355
00:17:58,923 --> 00:18:00,570
put it in an envelope like this

356
00:18:00,671 --> 00:18:04,455
and then all that's left is postage
so I can put it in the mailbox for you.

357
00:18:05,000 --> 00:18:06,323
- Postage?
- Yep.

358
00:18:06,423 --> 00:18:09,407
You just toss a penny over to me
so I can stamp it,

359
00:18:09,508 --> 00:18:10,880
and we're all ready to go.

360
00:18:11,958 --> 00:18:14,449
Couldn't you just put it in?

361
00:18:14,548 --> 00:18:16,148
Aw. Tsk.

362
00:18:16,383 --> 00:18:19,615
I really, really would, but I can't.

363
00:18:19,715 --> 00:18:22,449
It's not a letter
if it doesn't have postage.

364
00:18:22,548 --> 00:18:23,548
See how it works?

365
00:18:24,000 --> 00:18:25,000
So what do you say?

366
00:18:25,098 --> 00:18:27,201
I get my letter, and you get your
drawing.

367
00:18:27,300 --> 00:18:29,451
Win-win. You want your drawing, don't
you?

368
00:18:29,550 --> 00:18:31,268
- Um...
- If you don't, I'm gonna keep it.

369
00:18:31,367 --> 00:18:32,448
- Hmm.
- I love it.

370
00:18:32,548 --> 00:18:33,705
I would keep it if I was you,

371
00:18:33,806 --> 00:18:36,082
so I would send this letter
back to myself if I was you.

372
00:18:36,182 --> 00:18:37,212
[hounds growling]

373
00:18:37,875 --> 00:18:39,569
[boy] Oh, hi, Papa!

374
00:18:39,670 --> 00:18:42,570
This nice man says
he can mail my drawing back to me!

375
00:18:42,671 --> 00:18:45,385
- He's lying. Children are liars.
- [boy] Can you give him a penny?

376
00:18:45,486 --> 00:18:47,279
Oh, look at that. Wrong address. Silly
me.

377
00:18:47,380 --> 00:18:49,176
These aren't...
You're not the Spendlebergs.

378
00:18:49,277 --> 00:18:50,277
I'll see you later.

379
00:18:50,375 --> 00:18:52,174
Thank you so much,
and no need... [mumbling]

380
00:18:52,583 --> 00:18:55,059
- [hounds barking]
- [Jesper] Aah! The
puppies! The puppies!

381
00:18:55,160 --> 00:18:57,664
Ah. And that must be the express mail.

382
00:18:58,958 --> 00:19:00,276
[Jesper] All right, Smeerensburg.

383
00:19:00,375 --> 00:19:01,661
You may have won this round,

384
00:19:01,760 --> 00:19:04,073
but if you think I'm giving up,
think again.

385
00:19:04,173 --> 00:19:05,616
I'll have my letters in no time,

386
00:19:05,717 --> 00:19:08,199
and then it's bye-bye to you
and your cold and your loons

387
00:19:08,298 --> 00:19:09,976
and your chickens! That's right! You
too!

388
00:19:10,076 --> 00:19:11,076
[clucking]

389
00:19:11,174 --> 00:19:12,420
You'll see. I give it a week.

390
00:19:13,000 --> 00:19:14,079
Two, tops.

391
00:19:25,165 --> 00:19:26,536
[wood creaking]

392
00:19:30,000 --> 00:19:32,000
[hens clucking]

393
00:19:37,125 --> 00:19:40,069
Is this a bad time?
I can see you're pretty swamped.

394
00:19:40,170 --> 00:19:44,536
[sighs] Don't you have...

395
00:19:45,040 --> 00:19:46,951
a job or something?

396
00:19:47,050 --> 00:19:48,282
Why, sure I do.

397
00:19:48,383 --> 00:19:51,569
I'm here to pick up all the outgoing
mail.

398
00:19:51,670 --> 00:19:52,820
So, where is it?

399
00:19:52,921 --> 00:19:55,198
Now, you're gonna have to help me
with the heavier bags.

400
00:19:55,298 --> 00:19:56,298
Bad back, don't you know.

401
00:19:56,396 --> 00:19:58,740
- [Jesper] Man, I hate you.
- I know.

402
00:19:58,840 --> 00:20:01,411
So, uh, where is the mail, anyway?

403
00:20:01,510 --> 00:20:04,160
Where do you keep it?
In a different room now or something?

404
00:20:04,259 --> 00:20:06,281
What about if I walk around the room,

405
00:20:06,382 --> 00:20:10,319
if I get close to the mail,
you say "warmer"?

406
00:20:10,420 --> 00:20:15,125
And if I'm getting
farther from the mail, you say "colder"?

407
00:20:15,708 --> 00:20:16,877
- And then...
- What's that?

408
00:20:17,458 --> 00:20:19,199
What? Oh, the woodsman's cabin?

409
00:20:19,298 --> 00:20:21,160
[Jesper] Yeah, does someone live there?

410
00:20:21,259 --> 00:20:24,118
Well, sure.
Yeah, you should definitely drop by.

411
00:20:24,219 --> 00:20:27,248
Nice fella. Loves visitors.

412
00:20:44,250 --> 00:20:46,250
[bridge creaking]

413
00:21:15,958 --> 00:21:16,958
[grunts]

414
00:21:47,458 --> 00:21:49,458
[door creaking]

415
00:21:52,540 --> 00:21:56,701
Hello? I'm in your house
or... whatever this place is.

416
00:21:56,800 --> 00:21:57,881
Anybody here?

417
00:21:58,958 --> 00:21:59,998
[grunts softly]

418
00:22:04,875 --> 00:22:06,739
Ah, come on. Really?

419
00:22:06,838 --> 00:22:08,502
[grunting]

420
00:22:11,250 --> 00:22:13,920
Of course. Of course this would happen.

421
00:22:19,040 --> 00:22:21,750
Great. I'm gonna kill that boatman.

422
00:22:27,000 --> 00:22:28,000
What?

423
00:22:32,665 --> 00:22:33,665
Toys?

424
00:22:38,208 --> 00:22:39,208
Ah, here we go.

425
00:22:45,833 --> 00:22:50,869
Now I can go home with the satisfaction
of having accomplished absolutely...

426
00:22:50,970 --> 00:22:51,970
[grunting]

427
00:22:52,068 --> 00:22:53,365
[footsteps thudding]

428
00:22:53,465 --> 00:22:54,538
[whimpers] Aah!

429
00:23:01,415 --> 00:23:03,415
[playing music]

430
00:23:11,250 --> 00:23:12,460
[loud crash]

431
00:23:12,833 --> 00:23:14,034
[pants]

432
00:23:14,134 --> 00:23:15,134
[exclaims]

433
00:23:18,083 --> 00:23:19,083
Aah!

434
00:23:19,510 --> 00:23:20,710
[pants]

435
00:23:24,583 --> 00:23:25,583
[music stops]

436
00:23:25,682 --> 00:23:27,210
[panting]

437
00:23:29,875 --> 00:23:30,875
Aah!

438
00:23:36,333 --> 00:23:37,673
[screaming]

439
00:23:50,583 --> 00:23:51,583
[screams]

440
00:23:54,290 --> 00:23:55,451
[grunts]

441
00:23:55,550 --> 00:23:57,540
[whimpering and panting]

442
00:24:03,083 --> 00:24:04,083
Yeehaw!

443
00:24:08,500 --> 00:24:09,750
[footsteps approaching]

444
00:25:16,458 --> 00:25:18,117
That's it! I've had it!

445
00:25:18,218 --> 00:25:20,571
Better alive in the gutter
than hacked into pieces!

446
00:25:20,672 --> 00:25:21,915
No, thank you!

447
00:25:25,000 --> 00:25:26,000
Yah!

448
00:25:28,915 --> 00:25:30,698
[yelps and screams]

449
00:25:30,798 --> 00:25:31,798
[grunts]

450
00:25:35,290 --> 00:25:36,290
[gasps]

451
00:25:38,040 --> 00:25:41,921
[screams] Please don't chop me up
and scatter my parts in the woods!

452
00:25:45,958 --> 00:25:47,127
[whimpers]

453
00:25:47,958 --> 00:25:49,072
Where's this?

454
00:25:49,172 --> 00:25:51,366
What? I don't know. How would I...

455
00:25:51,467 --> 00:25:52,467
Wait.

456
00:25:53,125 --> 00:25:54,125
I do know.

457
00:25:54,223 --> 00:25:56,822
Keep going down this road,
and you'll get there.

458
00:25:56,922 --> 00:25:58,989
You can't miss it. It...
Or I can show you.

459
00:25:59,088 --> 00:26:01,173
Sure. Yeah, let me just show you.

460
00:26:11,040 --> 00:26:12,118
All right.

461
00:26:12,219 --> 00:26:13,219
[grunts]

462
00:26:13,317 --> 00:26:14,571
Excuse me. Just... Can I...

463
00:26:14,672 --> 00:26:15,672
[groans]

464
00:26:16,333 --> 00:26:17,333
Here we are.

465
00:26:17,432 --> 00:26:19,962
Watch your step getting out of the,
uh...
What's this?

466
00:26:20,875 --> 00:26:22,704
You're a postman, aren't you?

467
00:26:23,958 --> 00:26:25,458
Oh, you want me to... [chuckles]

468
00:26:26,040 --> 00:26:27,290
No, but I...

469
00:26:29,458 --> 00:26:31,248
[clears throat] Sure thing. My pleasure.

470
00:26:31,915 --> 00:26:32,993
Nothing I'd love to do more

471
00:26:33,094 --> 00:26:38,161
than deliver what I'm fairly certain
can only be a severed head of some kind.

472
00:26:38,260 --> 00:26:40,258
I mean, there's no way
that's not a severed head.

473
00:26:40,357 --> 00:26:42,866
It's gotta... I'm holding a head
in my hand, but hey!

474
00:26:42,967 --> 00:26:43,967
[grunts]

475
00:26:44,066 --> 00:26:46,035
Come on! Look, I'm...

476
00:26:46,625 --> 00:26:47,779
Ah! You're right there!

477
00:26:47,880 --> 00:26:50,656
So quiet for a disproportionately...

478
00:26:50,757 --> 00:26:53,573
- I mean, strapping, uh... statuesque.
- [growls]

479
00:26:53,673 --> 00:26:55,536
You have a kind of, um...

480
00:26:59,500 --> 00:27:00,700
What? In there?

481
00:27:00,799 --> 00:27:03,073
You must be kidding.
No way. Absolutely not.

482
00:27:03,173 --> 00:27:05,116
I mean, first of all,
I'd love to, of course,

483
00:27:05,217 --> 00:27:07,071
but, look, too bad about the fence.

484
00:27:07,172 --> 00:27:08,616
Rats. Oh, well.

485
00:27:08,717 --> 00:27:11,196
What are you gonna do? Are you...
What's happening right now?

486
00:27:12,500 --> 00:27:14,073
Hey, listen, please. Open this!

487
00:27:14,173 --> 00:27:16,407
- Why are you doing this to me?
- [hounds growling]

488
00:27:16,508 --> 00:27:17,508
Oh, no.

489
00:27:18,000 --> 00:27:20,000
[snarling]

490
00:27:20,259 --> 00:27:22,059
[barking]

491
00:27:22,549 --> 00:27:25,226
Okay, you win. What do you want?
Money? My dad's got plenty of it.

492
00:27:25,326 --> 00:27:27,521
You can write him a ransom note.
You can write, right?

493
00:27:27,622 --> 00:27:29,459
Oh, it doesn't matter.
I'll write it for you.

494
00:27:29,558 --> 00:27:32,661
Ah! He'll never know it's me!
I'll make it sound like it's from you!

495
00:27:32,760 --> 00:27:35,160
I'll use monosyllabic words, man!
Please! Please! Please!

496
00:27:35,259 --> 00:27:37,160
Just let me out of here!
I'm gonna get...

497
00:27:37,259 --> 00:27:38,660
[screams]

498
00:27:38,759 --> 00:27:39,759
Why?

499
00:27:42,333 --> 00:27:43,333
[screams]

500
00:27:43,432 --> 00:27:45,118
[grunts] Ow! Ow!

501
00:27:45,219 --> 00:27:46,577
- [man] Who's there?
- [gasps]

502
00:27:48,458 --> 00:27:49,877
[gasping]

503
00:27:53,583 --> 00:27:54,583
Aah!

504
00:27:54,682 --> 00:27:56,170
Door, door, door.

505
00:27:56,833 --> 00:27:57,923
[straining]

506
00:27:59,458 --> 00:28:01,038
Locks! [gasps]

507
00:28:02,290 --> 00:28:04,381
This has gotta move! Come on! Come on!

508
00:28:06,458 --> 00:28:08,199
Open up. Open up. Open up! Come on!

509
00:28:08,298 --> 00:28:09,540
Come on! Come on! Come on!

510
00:28:10,333 --> 00:28:13,742
Come on! Come on! Come on!
Keep it together! Keep it together!

511
00:28:13,843 --> 00:28:14,962
[exclaims]

512
00:28:16,000 --> 00:28:17,000
Aah!

513
00:28:17,708 --> 00:28:19,458
[hounds barking]

514
00:28:20,958 --> 00:28:21,958
[grunts]

515
00:28:22,375 --> 00:28:23,785
[whimpering]

516
00:28:24,583 --> 00:28:25,784
Where are they, boys?

517
00:28:25,884 --> 00:28:28,615
Don't let 'em get away! Come on! Get
'em!

518
00:28:28,715 --> 00:28:29,821
[gasps] Okay.

519
00:28:29,922 --> 00:28:31,779
I've done all you've asked. Can I
please...

520
00:28:31,880 --> 00:28:33,204
[muffled speech]

521
00:28:38,083 --> 00:28:40,333
[muffled speech]

522
00:28:43,375 --> 00:28:44,375
Hmm.

523
00:28:51,540 --> 00:28:52,540
[gasps]

524
00:29:01,790 --> 00:29:03,290
[chimes]

525
00:29:06,750 --> 00:29:07,829
[croaking]

526
00:29:09,000 --> 00:29:10,000
[gasps]

527
00:29:11,500 --> 00:29:12,500
[gasps]

528
00:29:13,458 --> 00:29:14,458
[giggles]

529
00:29:19,040 --> 00:29:20,830
[laughing]

530
00:29:40,665 --> 00:29:42,286
[gasps and pants]

531
00:29:43,540 --> 00:29:44,741
[giggles]

532
00:29:44,842 --> 00:29:45,842
[gasps]

533
00:29:45,941 --> 00:29:46,941
[gasps]

534
00:30:04,333 --> 00:30:06,333
[rooster crowing]

535
00:30:07,333 --> 00:30:09,752
[hens clucking]

536
00:30:12,000 --> 00:30:14,000
[muttering]

537
00:30:14,915 --> 00:30:15,915
Has he?

538
00:30:16,015 --> 00:30:18,250
- [pounding at door]
- Ah! He's here to finish the job!

539
00:30:18,351 --> 00:30:20,212
- Oh, no!
- [girl] Mr. Postman?

540
00:30:20,750 --> 00:30:22,039
Are you in there?

541
00:30:23,208 --> 00:30:24,998
Go away! Go! Leave! He'll hear you!

542
00:30:25,875 --> 00:30:28,204
We'd like to send these letters!

543
00:30:29,750 --> 00:30:32,200
[objects clattering]

544
00:30:32,299 --> 00:30:33,299
[hen clucking]

545
00:30:34,540 --> 00:30:36,282
What? What did you just say?

546
00:30:36,383 --> 00:30:39,865
Our cousin told us
if we write a letter to Mr. Klaus,

547
00:30:39,965 --> 00:30:40,990
he'll make us a toy.

548
00:30:41,089 --> 00:30:43,369
He also said to bring you a penny each.

549
00:30:43,470 --> 00:30:46,748
It's not a letter
if it doesn't have postage, right?

550
00:30:48,083 --> 00:30:49,923
["How You Like Me Now?" playing]

551
00:30:57,750 --> 00:30:59,573
- Psst. Hey. Hey, you.
- Hmm?

552
00:30:59,673 --> 00:31:00,673
You want a toy?

553
00:31:04,750 --> 00:31:06,950
- [chuckles]
- Hey! Would you, uh...

554
00:31:07,049 --> 00:31:08,049
like a brand-new toy?

555
00:31:08,665 --> 00:31:11,246
Just write a letter to Mr. Klaus.

556
00:31:12,500 --> 00:31:17,160
And you put it in the envelope,
write your name on it and bring a penny.

557
00:31:17,259 --> 00:31:18,329
Can't forget the penny.

558
00:31:35,540 --> 00:31:37,671
These better sound sad. Do they sound
sad?

559
00:31:38,250 --> 00:31:39,250
Okay, good job.

560
00:31:45,458 --> 00:31:47,958
All right. And now...

561
00:31:48,625 --> 00:31:49,704
<i>for the tricky part.</i>

562
00:31:59,790 --> 00:32:01,000
- [wood clatters]
- [gasps]

563
00:32:09,958 --> 00:32:11,327
- [wood splinters]
- [gasps]

564
00:32:13,083 --> 00:32:14,633
[wood creaking]

565
00:32:21,250 --> 00:32:22,250
[Klaus grunts]

566
00:32:23,750 --> 00:32:24,880
All right. Remember...

567
00:32:25,458 --> 00:32:27,577
probably not an ax murderer, though...

568
00:32:28,165 --> 00:32:30,915
it still is a possibility,
but most likely... no.

569
00:32:31,540 --> 00:32:33,461
He's a good guy... deep down.

570
00:32:34,415 --> 00:32:36,407
- [clears throat] Hello.
- [grunts]

571
00:32:36,508 --> 00:32:40,118
[clears throat] Hello.
Mr... Klaus, I take it?

572
00:32:40,219 --> 00:32:43,449
You remember me from the nice
breaking and entering last night?

573
00:32:43,548 --> 00:32:45,532
[chuckles] Jesper Johanssen, postman,

574
00:32:45,633 --> 00:32:48,198
- but we never properly...
- [grunts]

575
00:32:48,298 --> 00:32:50,080
[gulps] Uh...

576
00:32:50,625 --> 00:32:51,739
I, uh...

577
00:32:51,838 --> 00:32:56,201
You see, Mr. Klaus,
it seems like word got around

578
00:32:56,301 --> 00:33:00,160
that the poor children of Smeerensburg
have started, uh...

579
00:33:00,259 --> 00:33:01,781
completely unprompted...

580
00:33:01,882 --> 00:33:04,375
writing letters asking you for...

581
00:33:06,040 --> 00:33:07,461
toys. [coughs]

582
00:33:08,040 --> 00:33:09,201
So I figured

583
00:33:09,300 --> 00:33:11,823
you have the whole barn filled with toys

584
00:33:11,923 --> 00:33:14,570
just sitting there collecting dust,
so...

585
00:33:14,671 --> 00:33:15,671
[whimpers]

586
00:33:18,290 --> 00:33:21,131
Oh, God. Okay. This is it. Here it goes.

587
00:33:23,958 --> 00:33:24,958
[grunts]

588
00:33:28,583 --> 00:33:30,583
[chirping]

589
00:33:32,665 --> 00:33:35,448
- [all chirping]
- [Jesper] Oh, wow.

590
00:33:35,548 --> 00:33:37,211
That is...

591
00:33:38,625 --> 00:33:39,948
totally normal.

592
00:33:40,048 --> 00:33:42,451
Not a symptom of any mental illness
or anything.

593
00:33:42,550 --> 00:33:44,741
- [Klaus] Go away.
- Mr. Klaus, sir!

594
00:33:44,842 --> 00:33:46,911
Those little children... [grunts]

595
00:33:47,010 --> 00:33:49,531
...if you donate your old toys to
them...

596
00:33:49,632 --> 00:33:52,825
[pants] ...well,
I'll gladly deliver them for free!

597
00:33:59,375 --> 00:34:00,494
Mr. Klaus, wait!

598
00:34:01,165 --> 00:34:03,366
Please! [panting]

599
00:34:03,467 --> 00:34:06,788
Think of all the joy you'll bring
their miserable little lives!

600
00:34:07,708 --> 00:34:08,708
Look, here.

601
00:34:09,083 --> 00:34:10,202
Poor little Herlief.

602
00:34:10,302 --> 00:34:13,201
He only has sticks and stones
to play with. So sad.

603
00:34:13,300 --> 00:34:14,701
And this one,

604
00:34:14,800 --> 00:34:16,992
little Penny... Patty.

605
00:34:17,092 --> 00:34:18,992
Her doll was so old,

606
00:34:19,092 --> 00:34:21,702
it crumbled in her arms
when she came to me.

607
00:34:21,802 --> 00:34:24,541
And then Kristoff...
Little, ugly Kristoff.

608
00:34:25,333 --> 00:34:26,333
This little...

609
00:34:33,208 --> 00:34:34,628
Tonight, same time.

610
00:34:35,916 --> 00:34:39,780
Great! What, "same time"?
You mean, dead of night?

611
00:34:39,880 --> 00:34:42,157
- I can just take the toys now.
- No. I go with you.

612
00:34:42,257 --> 00:34:44,449
There's no need
for you to come with me, really.

613
00:34:44,550 --> 00:34:45,869
It might be against the law

614
00:34:45,969 --> 00:34:48,867
for a noncertified postman
to ride with me.

615
00:34:48,967 --> 00:34:50,288
I have to check the rule book.

616
00:34:50,875 --> 00:34:54,284
Great. Tonight, then. I'll see you then.
Good talk. Good talk.

617
00:34:57,250 --> 00:34:59,250
[laughing and exclaiming]

618
00:35:09,541 --> 00:35:10,541
[gasps]

619
00:35:10,639 --> 00:35:11,639
[gasps]

620
00:35:17,291 --> 00:35:19,380
- [children laughing]
- [hounds whining]

621
00:35:25,333 --> 00:35:27,284
Whoa! Whoo!

622
00:35:27,384 --> 00:35:28,384
[gasps]

623
00:35:28,791 --> 00:35:29,791
Huh?

624
00:35:29,889 --> 00:35:30,889
[giggles]

625
00:35:30,989 --> 00:35:31,989
[gasps]

626
00:35:32,088 --> 00:35:33,088
[woman gasps]

627
00:35:33,625 --> 00:35:35,489
- Oh, oh!
- [gasps]

628
00:35:35,588 --> 00:35:36,588
[gasps]

629
00:35:39,750 --> 00:35:40,750
[man] Playing!

630
00:35:40,849 --> 00:35:42,572
Playing, I tell you.

631
00:35:42,672 --> 00:35:43,989
With an Ellingboe!

632
00:35:44,088 --> 00:35:47,043
- [councilman 1] An Ellingboe, no less!
- [councilman 2] In all my years!

633
00:35:47,143 --> 00:35:48,782
- Did you all hear that?
- Unacceptable.

634
00:35:48,882 --> 00:35:50,800
- [man] I don't know how it happened.
- [yelps]

635
00:35:50,900 --> 00:35:52,333
I turned away for one second...

636
00:35:54,500 --> 00:35:55,990
And then I saw it.

637
00:35:56,090 --> 00:35:58,119
I brought her as soon as I could, sir.

638
00:35:58,219 --> 00:36:00,449
- That's just wrong! Wrong, I say!
- Inconceivable!

639
00:36:00,548 --> 00:36:02,619
- What are we going to do?
- Unthinkable!

640
00:36:02,719 --> 00:36:05,322
Hmm. This is bad. Very bad.

641
00:36:05,422 --> 00:36:08,530
Worst I've ever seen, really.
What were you thinking, kid?

642
00:36:08,630 --> 00:36:09,630
Don't you know that...

643
00:36:09,728 --> 00:36:12,876
Krums and Ellingboes don't mix.

644
00:36:13,541 --> 00:36:15,369
- But why?
- "Why?" he asks!

645
00:36:15,469 --> 00:36:17,106
- See what I mean?
- [councilwoman] Why?

646
00:36:17,206 --> 00:36:18,206
I don't know what to do!

647
00:36:18,750 --> 00:36:21,130
Please help us, miss! I beg you!

648
00:36:23,083 --> 00:36:24,083
[gasps]

649
00:36:24,181 --> 00:36:25,181
[squeals]

650
00:36:29,500 --> 00:36:32,420
Do you know what this is, little boy?

651
00:36:33,125 --> 00:36:36,724
This is tradition!

652
00:36:36,920 --> 00:36:42,907
Centuries of glorious hatred,
passed down through generations!

653
00:36:43,007 --> 00:36:45,822
There was the hundred-day brawl of '45.

654
00:36:45,922 --> 00:36:47,489
Which we totally won!

655
00:36:47,588 --> 00:36:49,492
The maritime game of chicken.

656
00:36:49,592 --> 00:36:52,293
The Great Mooning of '86.

657
00:36:52,833 --> 00:36:53,833
[gasps]

658
00:36:54,458 --> 00:36:56,572
So, if there's something we know...

659
00:36:56,672 --> 00:36:59,239
...going back as far as we can
remember...

660
00:36:59,338 --> 00:37:01,824
...it's that a Krum
despises an Ellingboe...

661
00:37:01,923 --> 00:37:05,456
...and an Ellingboe can't stand a Krum!

662
00:37:09,958 --> 00:37:11,867
That is why.

663
00:37:11,967 --> 00:37:12,967
[gasps]

664
00:37:13,067 --> 00:37:19,949
Now, I just know you didn't mean to
disrespect all of that heritage, right?

665
00:37:20,048 --> 00:37:23,119
- Right.
- And it won't happen again,

666
00:37:23,219 --> 00:37:24,538
will it?

667
00:37:25,541 --> 00:37:27,130
Of course not.

668
00:37:27,666 --> 00:37:30,916
Now, tell me all about
where this pretty thing came from.

669
00:37:35,625 --> 00:37:36,625
Ugh.

670
00:37:37,458 --> 00:37:40,577
Let me guess.
Leaving it at the gate not an option?

671
00:37:43,083 --> 00:37:45,333
You really have a way with words,
you know?

672
00:37:46,291 --> 00:37:49,081
Of course, you don't...
Of course, don't even answer that...

673
00:37:51,125 --> 00:37:52,125
[groans]

674
00:37:52,958 --> 00:37:54,538
I'm sorry! I'm sorry! I'm sorry!

675
00:37:55,708 --> 00:37:56,708
[grunts]

676
00:37:57,083 --> 00:37:58,382
Whoa, whoa, whoa. No, no, no!

677
00:37:58,958 --> 00:37:59,958
[screams]

678
00:38:00,056 --> 00:38:01,056
[grunts]

679
00:38:01,155 --> 00:38:02,869
Stop, stop, stop!

680
00:38:02,969 --> 00:38:04,538
Stop! Stop!

681
00:38:05,750 --> 00:38:06,750
Aah!

682
00:38:07,666 --> 00:38:08,876
[screaming]

683
00:38:13,458 --> 00:38:14,458
[groaning]

684
00:38:32,083 --> 00:38:33,083
[sighs]

685
00:38:34,375 --> 00:38:35,994
[snoring]

686
00:38:38,791 --> 00:38:39,951
Whoa! Whoa!

687
00:38:40,050 --> 00:38:41,322
[screams]

688
00:38:41,422 --> 00:38:43,496
- You rotten vermin!
- [children giggling]

689
00:38:44,916 --> 00:38:46,376
[yawning]

690
00:38:47,333 --> 00:38:49,130
- [child 1] Me, me, me!
- [child 2] Pick me!

691
00:38:49,231 --> 00:38:51,306
- [child 1] Out of the way!
- [child 3] Mine first!

692
00:38:51,407 --> 00:38:52,407
I want a bicycle!

693
00:38:52,505 --> 00:38:54,344
- Tell Mr. Klaus I want a bicycle!
- Shut up!

694
00:38:54,443 --> 00:38:56,280
- Take my letter! Take my letter!
- Mine! Me!

695
00:38:56,380 --> 00:38:57,458
Me first! Me first! A doll!

696
00:38:57,559 --> 00:39:00,449
-Me! Me! Me!
- Okay! Okay! Single line! Chop-chop!

697
00:39:00,548 --> 00:39:02,782
Fall back! All right. Everyone, in line.

698
00:39:02,882 --> 00:39:04,201
- There you go.
- Get out! Move.

699
00:39:04,300 --> 00:39:06,992
Letter? Good. Letter? Good.

700
00:39:07,092 --> 00:39:09,213
Got it. Get out of here.
Great. Move along.

701
00:39:11,750 --> 00:39:14,119
[speaking Saami]

702
00:39:14,219 --> 00:39:18,378
- What's wrong with her mouth?
- She's not from here. She's Saami.

703
00:39:19,041 --> 00:39:22,072
[speaking Saami]

704
00:39:22,172 --> 00:39:26,280
Right, that's nice. But I see no letter,
so please come back when you have one.

705
00:39:26,380 --> 00:39:27,380
Have a nice day.

706
00:39:27,478 --> 00:39:29,409
Bye-bye. Okay, any other letters?

707
00:39:29,509 --> 00:39:31,387
- [boy] Here! Here! Here!
- [girl] Me, me, me!

708
00:39:31,487 --> 00:39:32,844
Good. The rest, you know the deal.

709
00:39:32,945 --> 00:39:33,945
No letter, no toy.

710
00:39:34,043 --> 00:39:35,820
But we don't know how to write.

711
00:39:35,920 --> 00:39:37,320
[yawns]

712
00:39:37,630 --> 00:39:39,197
Tough luck, kid.

713
00:39:39,297 --> 00:39:41,331
Wait, you know what you could do?

714
00:39:53,083 --> 00:39:55,083
[whistling]

715
00:39:55,625 --> 00:39:57,157
- What are you doing?
- Aah!

716
00:39:57,257 --> 00:39:59,619
Telling children to go to school
to learn to write?

717
00:39:59,719 --> 00:40:00,719
What is wrong with you?

718
00:40:00,818 --> 00:40:02,280
Yeah, yes. What I meant to do...

719
00:40:02,380 --> 00:40:03,896
- Listen to me, Postman.
- [whimpers]

720
00:40:03,996 --> 00:40:06,070
Whatever you're doing, leave me out of
it.

721
00:40:06,170 --> 00:40:08,820
I have been rotting away here
for five years,

722
00:40:08,920 --> 00:40:10,320
and I am so close to getting out.

723
00:40:10,420 --> 00:40:12,101
I am not about to let you mess it all
up.

724
00:40:12,666 --> 00:40:13,666
You got it?

725
00:40:13,764 --> 00:40:17,030
These children wasting away
without a proper education?

726
00:40:17,130 --> 00:40:18,130
I mean...

727
00:40:18,228 --> 00:40:19,449
[chuckles]

728
00:40:19,548 --> 00:40:22,869
Forgive me, I'm kind of a dreamer,
but...
isn't that why we do it?

729
00:40:22,969 --> 00:40:24,030
Hmm? Hmm?

730
00:40:24,130 --> 00:40:25,947
Why you became a teacher?

731
00:40:26,047 --> 00:40:27,659
So you could make a difference?

732
00:40:27,760 --> 00:40:28,909
[groans]

733
00:40:29,010 --> 00:40:30,990
[grunts and huffs]

734
00:40:31,090 --> 00:40:32,119
[panting]

735
00:40:32,219 --> 00:40:34,449
Ah. Young love.

736
00:40:34,548 --> 00:40:35,659
Takes me back, you know?

737
00:40:35,760 --> 00:40:39,240
The intense looks,
the palpitation of the heart.

738
00:40:39,340 --> 00:40:41,742
The whimpering
and the soiling of the pants, no.

739
00:40:41,842 --> 00:40:43,284
I can't relate to so much.

740
00:40:43,384 --> 00:40:44,784
[sighs]

741
00:40:48,500 --> 00:40:50,822
So you go to sleep,
and when you wake up in the morning,

742
00:40:50,922 --> 00:40:52,721
the present is right there
by the fireplace!

743
00:40:52,820 --> 00:40:54,951
Yeah, Mr. Klaus is amazing!

744
00:40:55,050 --> 00:40:57,072
- [boy chuckles] Yeah, he's awesome.
- Yeah!

745
00:40:57,172 --> 00:40:59,157
"Klaus"? "Awesome"?

746
00:40:59,257 --> 00:41:02,119
He's huge,
but he can squeeze down any chimney!

747
00:41:02,219 --> 00:41:03,867
- Really? How?
- I don't know.

748
00:41:03,967 --> 00:41:04,967
Magic, I guess.

749
00:41:05,067 --> 00:41:06,670
Ow! [grunts]

750
00:41:08,666 --> 00:41:09,666
There.

751
00:41:09,764 --> 00:41:10,764
Ugh.

752
00:41:11,090 --> 00:41:12,992
If you leave your socks
hanging on the mantle,

753
00:41:13,092 --> 00:41:15,382
Mr. Klaus will fill them with toys!

754
00:41:17,916 --> 00:41:19,907
[girl] <i>He only comes when you're
sleeping.</i>

755
00:41:20,007 --> 00:41:21,740
No one has ever seen him.

756
00:41:21,840 --> 00:41:24,284
<i>- It's like he's invisible or something.</i>
- [boy snores]

757
00:41:24,384 --> 00:41:25,384
[Jesper exclaims]

758
00:41:26,041 --> 00:41:27,380
- Aah!
- [gasps]

759
00:41:28,166 --> 00:41:31,826
[girl] <i>Oh, and he likes cookies.</i>
<i>Don't forget to leave out some cookies.</i>

760
00:41:36,291 --> 00:41:37,291
[gasps]

761
