<i> Holy night </i>

1254
01:10:18,000 --> 01:10:19,199
Merry Christmas, Miss. Alva!

1255
01:10:19,300 --> 01:10:21,336
- Merry Christmas, Mr. Postman!
- Merry Christmas.

1256
01:10:21,435 --> 01:10:22,713
Good evening, Postman Johanssen.

1257
01:10:22,814 --> 01:10:23,814
- Hello.
- Miss. Alva.

1258
01:10:23,912 --> 01:10:25,041
[children giggling]

1259
01:10:31,250 --> 01:10:33,250
[children exclaiming and laughing]

1260
01:10:36,250 --> 01:10:38,630
Not quite the same place,
is it? [chuckles]

1261
01:10:41,457 --> 01:10:42,627
[straining]

1262
01:10:43,582 --> 01:10:44,582
[panting]

1263
01:10:45,207 --> 01:10:46,207
[knocking at door]

1264
01:10:49,250 --> 01:10:50,409
[speaking Saami]

1265
01:10:50,510 --> 01:10:51,510
[Jesper] Hey.

1266
01:10:52,041 --> 01:10:53,323
What're you doing here?

1267
01:10:53,422 --> 01:10:54,666
[visitors speaking Saami]

1268
01:11:03,750 --> 01:11:05,823
A true act of goodwill, huh?

1269
01:11:05,922 --> 01:11:07,626
Always sparks another.

1270
01:11:08,207 --> 01:11:09,207
Never fails.

1271
01:11:09,916 --> 01:11:12,820
Remember, put the letter in the
envelope.

1272
01:11:12,921 --> 01:11:15,557
- And pass it down the line.
- Come on! It doesn't have to rhyme.

1273
01:11:15,658 --> 01:11:18,333
- [Mrs. Krum] That's right, keep at it.
- Keep it short and sweet!

1274
01:11:18,434 --> 01:11:19,792
No extra points for good spelling.

1275
01:11:19,891 --> 01:11:22,846
- Oh, you're doing so great, pumpkin.
- [Mrs. Krum] Let's go! One letter!

1276
01:11:22,947 --> 01:11:25,703
[Mr. Ellingboe] Come on,
it doesn't have
to be Shakespeare, people.

1277
01:11:26,750 --> 01:11:27,750
[grunts]

1278
01:11:29,375 --> 01:11:30,375
Whoa!

1279
01:11:30,756 --> 01:11:32,880
Steady, ol' girl! Easy does it.

1280
01:11:35,791 --> 01:11:36,791
Oh, wow!

1281
01:11:40,250 --> 01:11:41,618
[indistinct chatter]

1282
01:11:41,719 --> 01:11:45,037
Uh-huh. Smooth lines. Good. Nice work.

1283
01:11:46,750 --> 01:11:47,750
Hello!

1284
01:11:48,541 --> 01:11:49,541
Hi.

1285
01:11:52,457 --> 01:11:53,780
[sighs]

1286
01:11:53,881 --> 01:11:55,994
What am I supposed to do, huh?

1287
01:11:57,082 --> 01:11:59,042
[Jesper] <i>Stay forever in this little
town?</i>

1288
01:12:02,957 --> 01:12:04,618
<i>Hanging out with an old woodsman?</i>

1289
01:12:04,717 --> 01:12:06,377
[upbeat music playing]

1290
01:12:07,707 --> 01:12:08,917
[laughing and cheering]

1291
01:12:10,791 --> 01:12:12,331
<i>Surrounded by crazy people?</i>

1292
01:12:14,666 --> 01:12:15,786
[Mrgu giggles]

1293
01:12:37,166 --> 01:12:38,826
<i>Never wanting anything more?</i>

1294
01:12:47,250 --> 01:12:51,170
- [indistinct chatter in Saami]
- [Mrgu giggling]

1295
01:12:53,666 --> 01:12:55,570
Okay, are you gonna do that part or...

1296
01:12:55,671 --> 01:12:57,198
How about you finish these and...

1297
01:12:57,297 --> 01:12:58,297
- [gasps]
- Whoa!

1298
01:13:00,125 --> 01:13:02,375
[women speaking Saami]

1299
01:13:05,041 --> 01:13:09,159
They insisted,
and I didn't want to be rude.

1300
01:13:09,260 --> 01:13:11,497
I don't know... What do you...
Pfft. It's a lot of red.

1301
01:13:11,596 --> 01:13:12,911
What do you... Is it too much?

1302
01:13:13,011 --> 01:13:14,409
- No.
- [knocking at door]

1303
01:13:14,510 --> 01:13:17,199
We'll just blindfold the reindeer
so they don't get dizzy.

1304
01:13:17,300 --> 01:13:19,136
- [chuckles] That's all. I'm kidding.
- Aw...

1305
01:13:19,237 --> 01:13:20,237
I'm kidding. I'm kidding.

1306
01:13:20,336 --> 01:13:22,332
It looks great. It looks good.
It's nice. It's...

1307
01:13:22,432 --> 01:13:23,432
Hello, Jesper.

1308
01:13:23,532 --> 01:13:24,779
Dad? What?

1309
01:13:24,880 --> 01:13:27,907
[clears throat] Sorry.
Let's, um... Let's talk outside.

1310
01:13:28,006 --> 01:13:29,460
It's a little cramped in here.

1311
01:13:32,125 --> 01:13:33,488
Dad, what're you doing here?

1312
01:13:33,588 --> 01:13:35,746
Time isn't up yet.
I've still got a few days until...

1313
01:13:35,845 --> 01:13:38,493
[chuckles] Fourteen thousand letters
out of Smeerensburg?

1314
01:13:38,592 --> 01:13:40,911
Well, I had to come and see it for
myself.

1315
01:13:41,011 --> 01:13:42,699
Dad, you can't just show up and...

1316
01:13:42,800 --> 01:13:44,573
Wait, what? 14,000?

1317
01:13:44,672 --> 01:13:47,117
- That's not right. It...
- [Mrs. Krum] Oh, but it is.

1318
01:13:47,216 --> 01:13:49,322
Don't be so modest.

1319
01:13:49,421 --> 01:13:50,448
What're they doing here?

1320
01:13:50,547 --> 01:13:53,264
They were the ones who alerted me
to what you've accomplished here.

1321
01:13:53,363 --> 01:13:56,533
We couldn't let such a feat go
unrewarded.

1322
01:13:56,634 --> 01:13:58,157
Listen, whatever they told you...

1323
01:13:58,256 --> 01:13:59,990
Well, then, ready to go?

1324
01:14:00,091 --> 01:14:01,452
Go? Where?

1325
01:14:01,551 --> 01:14:03,783
[chuckles] Home, of course.

1326
01:14:03,882 --> 01:14:07,125
A deal's a deal. The ordeal is over.

1327
01:14:08,125 --> 01:14:09,125
Home?

1328
01:14:09,457 --> 01:14:12,328
With the personal butler
and the breakfast in bed and...

1329
01:14:13,166 --> 01:14:14,238
my silk sheets?

1330
01:14:14,338 --> 01:14:16,533
No one deserves it more.

1331
01:14:16,634 --> 01:14:20,284
Wouldn't you agree, Mr. Klaus?

1332
01:14:22,916 --> 01:14:25,488
Oh, he was unbelievable!

1333
01:14:25,588 --> 01:14:29,119
Encouraging children to write letters
and go to school!

1334
01:14:29,220 --> 01:14:32,280
[Mr. Ellingboe] Convincing the locals
to donate their labor to...

1335
01:14:32,381 --> 01:14:34,664
such a worthy cause.

1336
01:14:35,332 --> 01:14:36,332
[Johanssen] Indeed.

1337
01:14:37,041 --> 01:14:38,751
Well, shall we then?

1338
01:14:40,541 --> 01:14:43,461
Perhaps a minute to say your goodbyes,
of course.

1339
01:14:47,041 --> 01:14:48,823
Please, I can explain.

1340
01:14:48,922 --> 01:14:50,908
- I was...
- Oh, it's very clear.

1341
01:14:51,007 --> 01:14:52,240
You just duped everyone

1342
01:14:52,341 --> 01:14:55,619
so you could get back to your
puffed-up life back in the big town.

1343
01:14:55,720 --> 01:14:56,720
Something like that?

1344
01:14:56,819 --> 01:15:01,570
No! No. Well, at first maybe, yes,
but, Alva, please come...

1345
01:15:01,671 --> 01:15:02,671
Alva, please come back.

1346
01:15:02,770 --> 01:15:06,618
If I, I didnt get the letters,
Id be cut off, but things changed!

1347
01:15:06,719 --> 01:15:08,408
[speaking Saami]

1348
01:15:08,509 --> 01:15:09,823
Jesper!

1349
01:15:09,922 --> 01:15:12,286
- [sobbing] Jesper!
- Mrgu...

1350
01:15:14,582 --> 01:15:16,283
Klaus, just listen. I...

1351
01:15:16,384 --> 01:15:18,574
Everybody's out to get something, right?

1352
01:15:41,041 --> 01:15:42,041
[Johanssen] I thought...

1353
01:15:42,140 --> 01:15:44,702
well, a bit of hardship
might help straighten you out,

1354
01:15:44,801 --> 01:15:46,701
but even I must admit that...

1355
01:15:46,801 --> 01:15:50,323
Well, let's just say that there's
certainly a bright future

1356
01:15:50,422 --> 01:15:53,738
for the man who brought postal service
to Smeerensburg, that's for sure.

1357
01:15:53,838 --> 01:15:57,082
And speaking of the future,
I look forward to discussing...

1358
01:16:01,541 --> 01:16:04,131
One down, one to go.

1359
01:16:06,000 --> 01:16:10,420
If you ask me "who" right now, I swear!

1360
01:16:26,541 --> 01:16:29,323
Well, now, finally leaving, aren't we?

1361
01:16:29,422 --> 01:16:31,496
[chuckles] I... uh...

1362
01:16:32,166 --> 01:16:33,238
Anchors away, Captain.

1363
01:16:33,338 --> 01:16:35,952
- We're sailing off at once.
- Well, that's a first.

1364
01:16:36,051 --> 01:16:37,051
I beg your pardon?

1365
01:16:37,150 --> 01:16:39,659
Never saw a postman
looking more miserable leaving

1366
01:16:39,760 --> 01:16:41,289
than on the day they came in.

1367
01:16:42,750 --> 01:16:45,073
Oh, well. Best leave it alone, I say.

1368
01:16:45,172 --> 01:16:47,238
I'm sure it's nothing that could fester

1369
01:16:47,338 --> 01:16:50,212
and eventually become
a source of resentment and regret.

1370
01:17:21,082 --> 01:17:22,382
[Mrgu] Jesper!

1371
01:17:23,082 --> 01:17:24,869
[panting]

1372
01:17:24,970 --> 01:17:26,457
[speaking Saami]

1373
01:17:31,916 --> 01:17:33,779
[sobbing] Jesper.

1374
01:17:33,880 --> 01:17:35,157
[speaking Saami]

1375
01:17:35,256 --> 01:17:36,460
[crying]

1376
01:17:37,957 --> 01:17:39,207
Cheer up, little one.

1377
01:17:41,625 --> 01:17:43,375
I think I may have missed my boat.

1378
01:17:44,125 --> 01:17:46,574
[gasps] Jesper!

1379
01:17:49,666 --> 01:17:51,626
[Jesper] So I told him.
I told him everything.

1380
01:17:52,166 --> 01:17:54,658
And then he turned to me, and he said...

1381
01:17:54,757 --> 01:17:56,710
[chuckles] ...he'd never been
more proud of me.

1382
01:17:57,207 --> 01:17:59,822
And he hugged me. Can you believe that?

1383
01:17:59,921 --> 01:18:01,117
I thought he'd be mad.

1384
01:18:01,216 --> 01:18:03,989
[speaking Saami]

1385
01:18:04,090 --> 01:18:05,493
Well, yeah, sure. I'll miss it.

1386
01:18:05,592 --> 01:18:09,911
The big house, the having my every whim
tended to, the silk sheets.

1387
01:18:10,011 --> 01:18:12,740
Oh, God, the silk sheets!
Can we change the subject?

1388
01:18:12,841 --> 01:18:15,119
[both laugh]

1389
01:18:15,220 --> 01:18:17,658
Anyways, anybody can get off a boat.

1390
01:18:17,759 --> 01:18:20,750
The real trick is gonna be
convincing
Klaus and Alva to give me an...

1391
01:18:21,582 --> 01:18:22,582
What? What's that?

1392
01:18:24,875 --> 01:18:25,875
It's the clans!

1393
01:18:27,832 --> 01:18:28,962
Klaus!

1394
01:18:32,457 --> 01:18:34,287
[man speaking Saami]

1395
01:18:37,875 --> 01:18:38,875
[Klaus] Slowly.

1396
01:18:39,457 --> 01:18:41,780
Slowly. Slowly.

1397
01:18:41,881 --> 01:18:42,954
A little bit...

1398
01:18:48,291 --> 01:18:49,461
[Mrs. Krum] Well, well.

1399
01:18:50,125 --> 01:18:51,865
Isn't this convenient?

1400
01:18:51,966 --> 01:18:53,207
[gasps and speaks Saami]

1401
01:18:54,041 --> 01:18:55,283
What're you doing here?

1402
01:18:55,382 --> 01:18:57,488
Why, we were just thinking,

1403
01:18:57,588 --> 01:19:01,243
"Don't our children
also deserve a present?"

1404
01:19:01,342 --> 01:19:02,573
And lookie here!

1405
01:19:02,673 --> 01:19:05,029
You've already got her favorite thing
in the world.

1406
01:19:05,130 --> 01:19:07,365
A nice, big piata!

1407
01:19:07,466 --> 01:19:09,618
- [all gasp]
- Hey, you put... [grunts]

1408
01:19:09,717 --> 01:19:11,739
...one hand on those toys and I swear
I...

1409
01:19:11,840 --> 01:19:13,243
Stand back. All right.

1410
01:19:13,342 --> 01:19:15,323
Do what you will with the toys.

1411
01:19:15,423 --> 01:19:16,867
But no one gets hurt.

1412
01:19:16,966 --> 01:19:19,198
Suits us just fine.

1413
01:19:19,298 --> 01:19:20,417
[Magdalone and Olaf grumble]

1414
01:19:20,516 --> 01:19:23,949
How long until children
go back to the old ways

1415
01:19:24,050 --> 01:19:26,831
once there are no toys to bribe them
with?

1416
01:19:27,416 --> 01:19:29,956
How long until they
turn against each other?

1417
01:19:30,791 --> 01:19:35,461
And how long until the grown-ups follow?

1418
01:19:36,666 --> 01:19:37,738
[gasps]

1419
01:19:37,838 --> 01:19:39,502
- [screams]
- [Jesper screaming]

1420
01:19:46,000 --> 01:19:47,118
Jesper?

1421
01:19:47,219 --> 01:19:48,287
The postman!

1422
01:19:52,707 --> 01:19:54,247
Ha! Eat our snow, you...

1423
01:19:54,916 --> 01:19:56,867
They're not attached.
Why aren't they attached?

1424
01:19:56,966 --> 01:19:58,125
I thought they were attached.

1425
01:19:58,225 --> 01:20:01,073
I would never, in a million years,
have done what I just did

1426
01:20:01,172 --> 01:20:02,689
if I didn't think these were attached.

1427
01:20:02,789 --> 01:20:03,789
After them!

1428
01:20:03,889 --> 01:20:07,240
Who leaves a sleigh
unattached like... Aah!

1429
01:20:07,341 --> 01:20:08,533
Destroy those toys!

1430
01:20:08,634 --> 01:20:10,865
- Stop them at any cost!
- Mine!

1431
01:20:10,966 --> 01:20:13,166
Mine! Mine!

1432
01:20:14,082 --> 01:20:15,332
- Mine!
- [Olaf chuckling]

1433
01:20:17,832 --> 01:20:19,792
[Magdalone in raspy voice] Mine...

1434
01:20:20,666 --> 01:20:21,666
Mine!

1435
01:20:30,207 --> 01:20:32,530
I could really use a hand here.

1436
01:20:32,631 --> 01:20:35,198
"Use." Interesting choice of word.

1437
01:20:35,297 --> 01:20:37,701
Really? You're gonna
go for the guilt trip now?

1438
01:20:37,801 --> 01:20:39,961
Smash those toys to pieces!

1439
01:20:45,957 --> 01:20:47,239
The toys!

1440
01:20:47,340 --> 01:20:49,661
- We have to close that bag!
- What do you care?

1441
01:20:49,761 --> 01:20:52,782
- I thought you were leaving.
- Great. Sure. I'll tell you what.

1442
01:20:52,881 --> 01:20:55,819
Let's continue discussing
what a horrible person I am

1443
01:20:55,920 --> 01:20:59,279
while I most likely break my neck
trying to save the children's toys,

1444
01:20:59,380 --> 01:21:01,448
- why don't we?
- Get down there!

1445
01:21:01,547 --> 01:21:03,211
- Stop those toys!
- [screaming]

1446
01:21:04,125 --> 01:21:05,125
[laughing]

1447
01:21:05,224 --> 01:21:06,711
Uh... Klaus?

1448
01:21:07,541 --> 01:21:08,541
Hmm.

1449
01:21:12,457 --> 01:21:13,787
[all scream]

1450
01:21:17,041 --> 01:21:20,033
Nice move! How'd you know
I wouldn't get knocked off too?

1451
01:21:20,132 --> 01:21:21,819
Never mind. Don't answer that.

1452
01:21:21,920 --> 01:21:22,920
[screams]

1453
01:21:23,582 --> 01:21:24,952
- Mine!
- [Jesper] Whoa!

1454
01:21:25,051 --> 01:21:27,201
Go! Go! We're dead!
We're dead! We're dead!

1455
01:21:27,301 --> 01:21:28,301
Mine!

1456
01:21:29,125 --> 01:21:31,784
- [growls] Mine!
- [exclaims]

1457
01:21:32,791 --> 01:21:33,791
[grunts]

1458
01:21:33,890 --> 01:21:35,202
[Mr. Ellingboe] Pumpkin!

1459
01:21:35,301 --> 01:21:37,461
I'm still proud of you, you hear me?

1460
01:21:38,166 --> 01:21:39,826
[ice cracking]

1461
01:21:40,625 --> 01:21:42,625
[exclaims]

1462
01:21:44,291 --> 01:21:45,291
Mine?

1463
01:21:54,082 --> 01:21:55,832
We're losing toys!

1464
01:21:56,332 --> 01:21:57,332
[grunts]

1465
01:21:57,431 --> 01:21:58,431
[gasps]

1466
01:22:00,582 --> 01:22:01,672
[both screaming]

1467
01:22:03,332 --> 01:22:04,332
[grunts]

1468
01:22:05,041 --> 01:22:07,033
- [all screaming]
- [Mrs. Krum] Oh, no!

1469
01:22:07,132 --> 01:22:09,090
- Stop! Stop!
- [Mr. Ellingboe] Oh, my goodness!

1470
01:22:09,189 --> 01:22:11,252
- Oh, no, no, no! No!
- [groans]

1471
01:22:13,082 --> 01:22:14,082
[Jesper screaming]

1472
01:22:16,250 --> 01:22:17,750
[grunting]

1473
01:22:20,707 --> 01:22:21,707
[groans]

1474
01:22:22,791 --> 01:22:23,791
[grunting]

1475
01:22:25,375 --> 01:22:27,319
Jesper! Let go!

1476
01:22:27,420 --> 01:22:30,036
- It's not worth it!
- Are you crazy? No!

1477
01:22:35,916 --> 01:22:36,916
[panting heavily]

1478
01:22:38,666 --> 01:22:39,666
[panting]

1479
01:22:40,625 --> 01:22:43,029
See? Nothing to it. Just...

1480
01:22:43,130 --> 01:22:45,414
[Mrs. Krum] I wouldn't be so sure.

1481
01:22:47,457 --> 01:22:48,957
Wait! No, no, no!

1482
01:22:49,457 --> 01:22:53,257
No! No, no, no! No!

1483
01:23:00,916 --> 01:23:05,070
This town was built
on resentment and spite.

1484
01:23:05,171 --> 01:23:08,070
And it'll stay that way
as long as a Krum...

1485
01:23:08,171 --> 01:23:09,367
Or an Ellingboe!

1486
01:23:09,466 --> 01:23:10,466
Ugh.

1487
01:23:10,565 --> 01:23:12,744
...have something to say about it.

1488
01:23:13,250 --> 01:23:15,990
Let's go. We're done here.

1489
01:23:16,091 --> 01:23:18,886
[Mr. Ellingboe] Well said.
Wait, does
that mean the feud is back on?

1490
01:23:18,987 --> 01:23:20,158
No more truce?

1491
01:23:20,257 --> 01:23:21,670
[Mrs. Krum] First thing tomorrow.

1492
01:23:22,791 --> 01:23:24,421
[Jesper] A true act of goodwill.

1493
01:23:25,416 --> 01:23:26,416
What was that?

1494
01:23:27,832 --> 01:23:28,832
[grunting]

1495
01:23:31,291 --> 01:23:33,581
A true act of goodwill...

1496
01:23:34,625 --> 01:23:36,324
always sparks another.

1497
01:23:37,041 --> 01:23:39,368
I think you hit your head
pretty hard, dear.

1498
01:23:39,469 --> 01:23:40,917
You should lie back down.

1499
01:23:41,500 --> 01:23:43,909
You don't believe me? Turn around.

1500
01:23:44,010 --> 01:23:45,010
What?

1501
01:23:45,750 --> 01:23:46,829
Turn around.

1502
01:23:50,832 --> 01:23:52,073
